I don&#39;t see where this is documented but the problem is that the current build artifact is also considered when checking for the `banTransitiveDependencies` rules. Then, [looking at the code](https://github.com/apache/maven-enforcer/blob/enforcer-1.4.1/enforcer-rules/src/main/java/org/apache/maven/plugins/enforcer/BanTransitiveDependencies.java#L95), since this artifact is excluded, it won&#39;t check its dependencies. So when you specify `*` for the exclude pattern, the main artifact matches that and the rest of the includes rules are ignored. So the following would work:

	&lt;rules&gt;
		&lt;banTransitiveDependencies&gt;
			&lt;excludes&gt;
				&lt;exclude&gt;commons-lang&lt;/exclude&gt;
			&lt;/excludes&gt;
			&lt;includes&gt;
				&lt;include&gt;commons-lang:commons-lang:2.4&lt;/include&gt;
			&lt;/includes&gt;
		&lt;/banTransitiveDependencies&gt;
	&lt;/rules&gt;

but it doesn&#39;t answer your question of &quot;Exclude banning all transitive dependencies, except commons-lang:2.4&quot;.

The question is, why are you using this rule in the first place? It was introduced in [MENFORCER-138](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MENFORCER-138) and its goal is to force developers to not rely on transitive dependencies being inherited and force their declaration in the POM.

Your goal here is to fail the build if the dependency `commons-lang:commons-lang:2.4` is in the classpath. Therefore, you should use the [`bannedDependencies`](https://maven.apache.org/enforcer/enforcer-rules/bannedDependencies.html) rule. By default, it searches dependencies transitively. The following will do what you want, i.e. ban only `commons-lang:commons-lang:2.4`:

	&lt;rules&gt;
		&lt;bannedDependencies&gt;
			&lt;excludes&gt;
				&lt;exclude&gt;commons-lang:commons-lang:2.4&lt;/exclude&gt;
			&lt;/excludes&gt;
		&lt;/bannedDependencies&gt;
	&lt;/rules&gt;

